Then he throws you
off a freeway overpass.

263
00:10:58,510 --> 00:11:00,090
And you figured
you'd skip step one.

264
00:11:00,110 --> 00:11:01,990
Ah, you don't want
to kill yourself, Leonard.

265
00:11:02,010 --> 00:11:03,390
How do you know?

266
00:11:03,410 --> 00:11:05,390
You enjoy a good
pastrami sandwich too much.

267
00:11:05,410 --> 00:11:07,190
It's not like I've got
other options here.

268
00:11:07,210 --> 00:11:10,200
I'm tapped out,
asset-Free.

269
00:11:10,900 --> 00:11:12,990
Cpa in another life.

270
00:11:13,010 --> 00:11:14,500
Friends with money?

271
00:11:17,600 --> 00:11:18,690
I hate pain.

272
00:11:18,710 --> 00:11:20,900
That's very sensible,
Mr. Steinberg.

273
00:11:21,600 --> 00:11:25,300
Leonard, supposing I wanted
to get in touch with Jimmy.

274
00:11:26,800 --> 00:11:28,600
How would I go about it?

275
00:11:33,300 --> 00:11:34,900
You came back, I see.

276
00:11:36,700 --> 00:11:38,000
Dr. Gallagher.

277
00:11:38,100 --> 00:11:39,990
The truth is,
I never really left.

278
00:11:40,010 --> 00:11:42,590
I have another meeting across
the street in 20 minutes.

279
00:11:42,610 --> 00:11:45,000
It was quiet here, so...

280
00:11:45,400 --> 00:11:50,090
I have 131 messages
and e-Mails to return.

281
00:11:50,110 --> 00:11:50,900
Wow.

282
00:11:51,100 --> 00:11:52,200
Yeah.

283
00:11:53,200 --> 00:11:56,300
Sorry if I broke any rules.

284
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,400
Well, you don't seem to have
done any permanent harm.

285
00:12:02,800 --> 00:12:05,300
You know, I admire
the work you do.

286
00:12:05,700 --> 00:12:09,990
I even admire what you're
trying to do for Trey Hansen.

287
00:12:10,010 --> 00:12:12,700
Does that mean you're gonna
go easy on me in court?

288
00:12:14,200 --> 00:12:17,300
Now, what did our friend
from the p. D.'S office tell you about me?

289
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:22,300
That you're a legend -
Unstoppable, never lose a case.

290
00:12:22,500 --> 00:12:24,200
Destined
for great things -

291
00:12:24,300 --> 00:12:27,500
Politics, private practice,
write your own ticket.

292
00:12:28,300 --> 00:12:30,200
She mention my nickname?

293
00:12:32,500 --> 00:12:33,800
"The great white. "

294
00:12:33,900 --> 00:12:35,400
Flattering...

295
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:37,290
Till you stop to consider

296
00:12:37,310 --> 00:12:39,200
It's Trey Hansen's blood
in the water.

297
00:12:42,500 --> 00:12:44,190
It's never personal.

298
00:12:44,210 --> 00:12:45,100
Really?

299
00:12:47,100 --> 00:12:48,700
Come with me.

300
00:13:01,300 --> 00:13:04,090
I shouldn't be here without
Mr. Hansen's attorney present.

301
00:13:04,110 --> 00:13:05,690
He can't see you,
can't hear you.

302
00:13:05,710 --> 00:13:06,900
Even so...

303
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:08,790
Trey Hansen lives
with his grandmother.

304
00:13:08,810 --> 00:13:10,500
He has since he was 6.

305
00:13:10,900 --> 00:13:12,000
I know that.

306
00:13:12,100 --> 00:13:13,090
He works, he comes home,

307
00:13:13,110 --> 00:13:14,490
And the two of them
cook supper together,

308
00:13:14,510 --> 00:13:15,900
And then they watch tv.

309
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:18,790
Their favorite thing to do on
the weekends is go to the zoo.

310
00:13:18,810 --> 00:13:22,300
He's terrified. He won't
last even a day in prison.

311
00:13:22,800 --> 00:13:27,300
Now, tell me -
How is that not personal?

312
00:13:28,200 --> 00:13:29,600
I don't make the law.

313
00:13:31,400 --> 00:13:33,500
Whatever happened to the
victim's stolen wallet?

314
00:13:34,800 --> 00:13:36,190
It was never found.

315
00:13:36,210 --> 00:13:38,900
Absence of evidence
is not evidence.

316
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:43,100
You should have
taken the deal.

317
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:04,590
Your honor,
members of the jury,

318
00:14:04,610 --> 00:14:06,590
We come here today
seeking justice.

319
00:14:06,610 --> 00:14:08,590
The facts in this case
are brutally simple.

320
00:14:08,610 --> 00:14:11,390
On the evening
of november 12, 2005,

321
00:14:11,410 --> 00:14:13,890
Andrew Wohl -
Age 35, happily married,

322
00:14:13,910 --> 00:14:16,890
With two children,
kevin, 8, and andrea, 6-

323
00:14:16,910 --> 00:14:19,490
Entered Rock Garden - It's
a sports bar in west L.A. -

324
00:14:19,510 --> 00:14:22,490
With the intention
of meeting two friends,

325
00:14:22,510 --> 00:14:26,000
Having a beer, and watching
the game on the big-Screen tv.

326
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:33,500
You will hear testimony
from the victim's two friends,

327
00:14:33,700 --> 00:14:35,490
Mr. Greer and Mr. Walker,

328
00:14:35,510 --> 00:14:37,290
Describing an altercation
that occurred

329
00:14:37,310 --> 00:14:40,100
Between Mr. Wohl and Trey Hansen
in this case...

330
00:14:42,500 --> 00:14:45,600
How Trey Hansen went a little
overboard with his drinking...

331
00:14:45,800 --> 00:14:46,700
Ugh!

332
00:14:47,300 --> 00:14:49,000
...and his demeanor.

333
00:14:49,100 --> 00:14:50,200
Don't touch me!

334
00:14:50,400 --> 00:14:52,990
Hey, man, what is your problem, man?
Nothing.

335
00:14:53,010 --> 00:14:54,300
I'm talking to you.

336
00:14:54,700 --> 00:14:55,990
You will hear, as well,

337
00:14:56,010 --> 00:14:59,300
The testimony of the bartender,
jason garcetti.

338
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:10,100
Ms. Crane?

339
00:15:11,100 --> 00:15:12,800
Sorry, your honor.

340
00:15:14,100 --> 00:15:16,590
The defendant
was subsequently ejected

341
00:15:16,610 --> 00:15:18,990
From the rock garden by
the bartender, jason garcetti.

342
00:15:19,010 --> 00:15:19,490
Get off, man!

343
00:15:19,510 --> 00:15:21,400
Get off!
No, I'm not leaving!

344
00:15:22,700 --> 00:15:24,800
Now, it should have
ended there, but it didn't.

345
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:27,090
About an hour later,
with the game nearly over,

346
00:15:27,110 --> 00:15:30,890
Andrew Wohl left rock garden
and his friends

347
00:15:30,910 --> 00:15:33,000
To return home to his family.

348
00:15:34,400 --> 00:15:36,200
He never arrived.

349
00:16:05,600 --> 00:16:06,990
Acting on descriptions

350
00:16:07,010 --> 00:16:09,390
From Mr. Greer,
Mr. Walker, Mr. Garcetti,

351
00:16:09,410 --> 00:16:12,000
And others that were present
at the rock garden that evening,

352
00:16:12,300 --> 00:16:16,200
The police traced Trey Hansen
to his home.

353
00:16:16,400 --> 00:16:18,890
They found there
a hooded sweatshirt and jeans

354
00:16:18,910 --> 00:16:21,290
Stained with the victim's blood.

355
00:16:21,310 --> 00:16:23,900
Also, they found
the murder weapon.

356
00:16:25,600 --> 00:16:29,290
They found a diary entry
in Mr. Hansen's diary,

357
00:16:29,310 --> 00:16:31,500
Describing the attack in detail.

358
00:16:32,200 --> 00:16:34,900
Confronted with this evidence,

359
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:37,090
Mr. Hansen confessed

360
00:16:37,110 --> 00:16:39,390
To the murder and robbery
of Andrew Wohl,

361
00:16:39,410 --> 00:16:41,700
A confession
that was later withdrawn.

362
00:16:42,500 --> 00:16:45,890
We come here today
seeking justice,

363
00:16:45,910 --> 00:16:47,990
Justice for the murder
of Andrew Wohl,

364
00:16:48,010 --> 00:16:50,390
Justice for his grief-Stricken
family and friends,

365
00:16:50,410 --> 00:16:53,800
Justice for a heinous,
tragic crime.

366
00:16:54,100 --> 00:16:57,990
We look to you,
members of the jury,

367
00:16:58,010 --> 00:16:59,600
For justice.

368
00:17:05,500 --> 00:17:08,600
Ms. Conivar,
your opening statement.

369
00:17:16,600 --> 00:17:18,090
Is this inappropriate
contact?

370
00:17:18,110 --> 00:17:19,100
Yes.

371
00:17:19,300 --> 00:17:20,890
But it's not punishable

372
00:17:20,910 --> 00:17:23,190
Unless I attempt
to influence your testimony,

373
00:17:23,210 --> 00:17:24,790
Or you my performance.

374
00:17:24,810 --> 00:17:26,400
Neither of which
is possible.

375
00:17:26,700 --> 00:17:28,990
It's punishable to try.
Punishable - That's a good word.

376
00:17:29,010 --> 00:17:30,500
That's a prosecutor's word.

377
00:17:30,700 --> 00:17:33,190
Not right or wrong,
nor good or evil - Punishable.

378
00:17:33,210 --> 00:17:35,190
It's how
we administer justice.

379
00:17:35,210 --> 00:17:36,600
In your world.

380
00:17:37,300 --> 00:17:39,800
Speaking of which,
you were brilliant.

381
00:17:40,300 --> 00:17:42,900
See, there's no way that
you could know this, doctor,

382
00:17:43,100 --> 00:17:43,900
But...

383
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:46,290
The trial's
already over.

384
00:17:46,310 --> 00:17:47,290
And that's justice?

385
00:17:47,310 --> 00:17:48,700
That's reality.

386
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:50,590
See, I have
a sympathetic victim,

387
00:17:50,610 --> 00:17:52,790
A nervous defendant,
strong evidence, and -

388
00:17:52,810 --> 00:17:54,200
And you never lose.

389
00:17:56,500 --> 00:17:58,000
Someday I will.

390
00:17:59,400 --> 00:18:00,700
Not today.

391
00:18:01,700 --> 00:18:03,390
One question, counselor.

392
00:18:03,410 --> 00:18:05,390
If your case
is so airtight,

393
00:18:05,410 --> 00:18:07,900
Why did you offer a plea bargain
to the defense?

394
00:18:08,300 --> 00:18:10,700
It couldn't be an act
of mercy, now, could it?

395
00:18:25,200 --> 00:18:26,790
How much time do I have?

396
00:18:26,810 --> 00:18:29,290
Prosecution witnesses
then another recess -

397
00:18:29,310 --> 00:18:30,990
A couple of hours,
at least.

398
00:18:31,010 --> 00:18:32,890
Okay, I'll be back in time
for my testimony.

399
00:18:32,910 --> 00:18:34,800
I'll keep it moving along.

400
00:18:39,600 --> 00:18:40,690
Is he in my office?

401
00:18:40,710 --> 00:18:42,290
Hey, Jimmy brought
his bodyguard.

402
00:18:42,310 --> 00:18:43,790
Two against two -
Fair fight.

403
00:18:43,810 --> 00:18:45,800
Uh, you haven't seen
the bodyguard.

404
00:18:48,700 --> 00:18:50,000
You got it?

405
00:18:51,500 --> 00:18:52,090
Got it.

406
00:18:52,110 --> 00:18:52,990
How much?

407
00:18:53,010 --> 00:18:54,400
$15.95.

408
00:18:56,500 --> 00:18:57,800
Let's go.

409
00:19:00,600 --> 00:19:02,090
Old-fashioned sit-down

410
00:19:02,110 --> 00:19:05,100
In a shrink's office -
That's a first.

411
00:19:05,600 --> 00:19:07,690
Leonard Steinberg
owes you 56k.

412
00:19:07,710 --> 00:19:09,200
Plus the vig.

413
00:19:10,200 --> 00:19:11,490
There's no way he can pay.

414
00:19:11,510 --> 00:19:12,500
Nice meeting you.

415
00:19:12,600 --> 00:19:13,800
Wait.

416
00:19:16,800 --> 00:19:18,600
In case you forgot yours.

417
00:19:18,800 --> 00:19:20,290
This cost me $15.95.

418
00:19:20,310 --> 00:19:23,200
It's gonna
cost you $56,000...

419
00:19:24,100 --> 00:19:25,500
...plus the vig.

420
00:19:28,500 --> 00:19:30,200
Lay it out for me.

421
00:19:32,400 --> 00:19:35,890
Leonard's cut off for good.
He's out of options.

422
00:19:35,910 --> 00:19:38,490
He's a compulsive gambler.
He needs treatment, not action.

423
00:19:38,510 --> 00:19:40,090
I'm in the action business.

424
00:19:40,110 --> 00:19:41,790
Give him a year
to get back on his feet.

425
00:19:41,810 --> 00:19:44,290
Then he starts paying the
interest at a reasonable -

426
00:19:44,310 --> 00:19:45,490
Reasonable rate.

427
00:19:45,510 --> 00:19:46,790
Can't do it, doc.

428
00:19:46,810 --> 00:19:49,090
Worrying about bad debts
keeps me up nights,

429
00:19:49,110 --> 00:19:51,100
And I'm way down on sleep.

430
00:19:51,400 --> 00:19:53,690
How many nights,
say, in a month?

431
00:19:53,710 --> 00:19:54,690
Why?

432
00:19:54,710 --> 00:19:58,200
How many hours sleep would you
say you average on a night?

433
00:19:58,300 --> 00:19:59,490
Three, four.

434
00:19:59,510 --> 00:20:01,490
Three or four? That's not
enough. You need at least six.

435
00:20:01,510 --> 00:20:03,790
Sleep disorder is among the most
common psychological problems

436
00:20:03,810 --> 00:20:05,790
We deal with...
and the most serious.

437
00:20:05,810 --> 00:20:07,200
How's your
medical insurance?

438
00:20:07,800 --> 00:20:09,500
You're looking at him.

439
00:20:12,900 --> 00:20:13,990
well, there's this clinic.

440
00:20:14,010 --> 00:20:15,890
It's hard to get into,
but I've got some influence.

441
00:20:15,910 --> 00:20:17,390
Maybe we can work
something out.

442
00:20:17,410 --> 00:20:19,000
That's all you got?

443
00:20:24,100 --> 00:20:27,200
Maybe not.
Who does your taxes?

444
00:20:27,700 --> 00:20:29,190
My sister's third husband.

445
00:20:29,210 --> 00:20:30,390
The government's
eating me alive,

446
00:20:30,410 --> 00:20:32,690
And idiot boy's
setting the table.

447
00:20:32,710 --> 00:20:34,500
Leonard is a cpa.

448
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:38,690
75% of his hourly rate
goes to paying the debt.

449
00:20:38,710 --> 00:20:40,090
What's in it for you?

450
00:20:40,110 --> 00:20:42,090
9th inning, 2 down.
Your team's one up.

451
00:20:42,110 --> 00:20:43,600
They've got two runners on,

452
00:20:44,100 --> 00:20:45,290
And their best hitter's
at the plate.

453
00:20:45,310 --> 00:20:46,300
What do you do?

454
00:20:46,600 --> 00:20:47,790
Bring in a closer.

455
00:20:47,810 --> 00:20:49,490
What if your closer
strikes him out?

456
00:20:49,510 --> 00:20:50,590
Gets a save.

457
00:20:50,610 --> 00:20:52,500
Well, that's what's in it
for me.

458
00:20:54,800 --> 00:20:56,700
Just the occasional save.

459
00:20:58,000 --> 00:20:59,900
I love baseball.

460
00:21:05,500 --> 00:21:07,890
Conivar: based on your tests
and observations, doctor,

461
00:21:07,910 --> 00:21:10,490
How would you describe Trey Hansen's
psychological condition

462
00:21:10,510 --> 00:21:12,890
Now and at the time
of the murder?

463
00:21:12,910 --> 00:21:14,690
He suffered then
as he suffers now -

464
00:21:14,710 --> 00:21:17,690
From a tendency towards
magical thinking and misattribution.

465
00:21:17,710 --> 00:21:20,100
Can you define those terms
for us?

466
00:21:20,300 --> 00:21:22,390
Well, magical thinking
is pretty much as it sounds -

467
00:21:22,410 --> 00:21:25,190
A belief in non-Causal,
nonscientific events,

468
00:21:25,210 --> 00:21:27,490
Confusing fantasy
with reality.

469
00:21:27,510 --> 00:21:28,990
Misattribution,
on the other hand,

470
00:21:29,010 --> 00:21:31,090
Is having or believing in
false memories.

471
00:21:31,110 --> 00:21:33,690
And could Mr. Hansen's
relatively low I.Q.

472
00:21:33,710 --> 00:21:35,590
Be a contributing factor?

473
00:21:35,610 --> 00:21:37,690
Yes, although
both conditions

474
00:21:37,710 --> 00:21:40,790
can occur in highly intelligent,
highly educated individuals.

475
00:21:40,810 --> 00:21:43,690
And those conditions
could explain the defendant's

476
00:21:43,710 --> 00:21:47,090
initial confession
and diary entry?

477
00:21:47,110 --> 00:21:48,790
We can't know for certain
what happened in that bar.

478
00:21:48,810 --> 00:21:50,600
There are
conflicting accounts.

479
00:21:50,800 --> 00:21:54,290
And if Mr. Hansen wasn't
the aggressor, as he contends -

480
00:21:54,310 --> 00:21:56,190
And especially given
his inebriated state -

481
00:21:56,210 --> 00:21:58,900
It's possible that he concocted
a revenge fantasy.

482
00:21:59,600 --> 00:22:03,200
Then later, when confronted
with Mr. Wohl's murder,

483
00:22:03,600 --> 00:22:05,100
He took it further,

484
00:22:05,600 --> 00:22:07,790
Imagining himself
as the slayer.

485
00:22:07,810 --> 00:22:09,490
That's why he picked up
the knife - his knife -

486
00:22:09,510 --> 00:22:10,900
And brought it home.

487
00:22:11,300 --> 00:22:13,790
And he recorded
that fantasy in his diary,

488
00:22:13,810 --> 00:22:18,000
Later recounting the fantasy
as his story to the police.

489
00:22:26,800 --> 00:22:28,290
So, how was court today?

490
00:22:28,310 --> 00:22:29,800
Pretty much
as I expected.

491
00:22:30,400 --> 00:22:31,790
Who are we
waiting on?

492
00:22:31,810 --> 00:22:33,700
At least one,
maybe two.

493
00:22:34,200 --> 00:22:35,600
What's up there?

494
00:22:35,900 --> 00:22:39,000
Oh, bed, bath, closet, you know.
You renting?

495
00:22:39,300 --> 00:22:41,290
It's all I could find on
the internet on short notice.

496
00:22:41,310 --> 00:22:42,800
Is this your family?

497
00:22:42,900 --> 00:22:45,090
It's my mum and dad,
sister, and I.

498
00:22:45,110 --> 00:22:47,300
Dad died about a year
after that was taken.

499
00:22:47,600 --> 00:22:49,600
Oh. I'm sorry.

500
00:22:52,400 --> 00:22:53,790
Mum remarried
a couple of years later

501
00:22:53,810 --> 00:22:55,990
To an american naval officer
serving with n. A.T.O.

502
00:22:56,010 --> 00:22:57,790
When his tour ended,
he brought us back to the u. S.

503
00:22:57,810 --> 00:23:00,100
They retired recently
to florida.

504
00:23:00,600 --> 00:23:01,800
And your sister?

505
00:23:03,700 --> 00:23:06,000
I haven't seen becky
in four years.

506
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:08,200
That's a long time.

507
00:23:12,300 --> 00:23:13,200
I'll go.

508
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:18,090
What are you
doing here?

509
00:23:18,110 --> 00:23:19,500
Playing poker.

510
00:23:20,200 --> 00:23:21,800
not with me, you're not.

511
00:23:22,500 --> 00:23:23,290
You want me to go.

512
00:23:23,310 --> 00:23:26,000
Yes. No, no.

513
00:23:31,800 --> 00:23:33,000
Look who I found!

514
00:23:34,500 --> 00:23:36,300
I can't even
buy a hand.

515
00:23:37,600 --> 00:23:41,200
All right. The pot's good.
Three players.

516
00:23:45,100 --> 00:23:45,690
Bets.

517
00:23:45,710 --> 00:23:47,300
Four bucks.

518
00:23:48,300 --> 00:23:50,400
Raise you.
Mm-Hmm.

519
00:23:54,800 --> 00:23:56,000
Call.

520
00:23:56,700 --> 00:23:57,900
Re-Raise.

521
00:24:00,800 --> 00:24:02,000
Again.

