00:24:08,800 --> 00:24:09,600
Call.

523
00:24:18,400 --> 00:24:19,790
Last card.

524
00:24:19,810 --> 00:24:21,700
Uh, check.

525
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:26,900
Bet.

526
00:24:31,700 --> 00:24:32,900
Raise.

527
00:24:34,400 --> 00:24:35,700
Call.

528
00:24:37,400 --> 00:24:38,300
Call.

529
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:41,400
On their backs.

530
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:43,600
Three of a kind.

531
00:24:43,700 --> 00:24:44,590
Straight.

532
00:24:44,610 --> 00:24:46,200
Ohh!

533
00:24:52,300 --> 00:24:54,000
you had to bet?

534
00:24:54,700 --> 00:24:57,490
Yes. I flopped a nut straight.
Of course I had to bet.

535
00:24:57,510 --> 00:25:00,100
Couldn't you know that he -
That he caught the flush?

536
00:25:01,300 --> 00:25:01,990
<i>Had you beat.</i>

537
00:25:02,010 --> 00:25:03,990
Oh, god. Unbelievable!

538
00:25:04,010 --> 00:25:04,890
Read a book
or something.

539
00:25:04,910 --> 00:25:06,900
Learn how to play
the game.

540
00:25:07,800 --> 00:25:08,900
You're the expert.

541
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:13,200
There's frozen yogurt
in the freezer.

542
00:25:16,700 --> 00:25:19,290
Okay, good night.
Night.

543
00:25:19,310 --> 00:25:20,290
I'll walk you out.

544
00:25:20,310 --> 00:25:21,800
Oh, no, don't bother.

545
00:25:31,100 --> 00:25:32,290
Hey, thanks for everything.

546
00:25:32,310 --> 00:25:34,600
Yeah. We're on again
next month.

547
00:25:38,600 --> 00:25:41,300
Do me a favor - Don't cash this
for a day or two, all right?

548
00:25:41,500 --> 00:25:42,790
I know you're
good for it.

549
00:25:42,810 --> 00:25:44,900
Nothing like
a friendly game, huh?

550
00:26:09,100 --> 00:26:11,090
Uh, Dr. Moore
requested a psych consult.

551
00:26:11,110 --> 00:26:12,800
Right here.
Thank you.

552
00:26:17,800 --> 00:26:18,900
I need help.

553
00:26:19,200 --> 00:26:19,890
not here.

554
00:26:19,910 --> 00:26:21,990
See me tonight.
I can't.

555
00:26:22,010 --> 00:26:22,890
I'm dying.

556
00:26:22,910 --> 00:26:24,200
Uh-huh.

557
00:26:28,100 --> 00:26:29,500
I'll try.

558
00:26:33,100 --> 00:26:34,800
Thank you, doctor.

559
00:26:35,600 --> 00:26:37,290
Is this real
ice cream?

560
00:26:37,310 --> 00:26:38,800
Real soy ice cream.

561
00:26:39,600 --> 00:26:40,890
Don't think
I'm not grateful.

562
00:26:40,910 --> 00:26:42,790
You got to get
used to the taste.

563
00:26:42,810 --> 00:26:45,590
I'm talking about Jimmy,
what you did for me.

564
00:26:45,610 --> 00:26:47,790
I just don't think
it can work.

565
00:26:47,810 --> 00:26:48,700
Why not?

566
00:26:49,100 --> 00:26:51,390
I'm gonna get the urge,
Dr. Gallagher.

567
00:26:51,410 --> 00:26:54,690
Maybe not for a while.
Maybe I'd fight it.

568
00:26:54,710 --> 00:26:57,090
But when it hits,
it's gonna hit hard,

569
00:26:57,110 --> 00:26:59,790
And I'm gonna be looking
for someone to take my action.

570
00:26:59,810 --> 00:27:02,200
Jimmy's not the only fish
in the pond.

571
00:27:03,200 --> 00:27:04,900
You walk
out of here tonight,

572
00:27:05,400 --> 00:27:06,890
How long before
you're back on the roof?

573
00:27:06,910 --> 00:27:08,690
What if it's better
this time?

574
00:27:08,710 --> 00:27:11,800
My losing streak's got to
take a turn sooner or later.

575
00:27:12,300 --> 00:27:14,590
Jimmy went over
your losses with me.

576
00:27:14,610 --> 00:27:16,090
Now, you usually bet
on the favorite, right?

577
00:27:16,110 --> 00:27:17,400
Sit down for a minute.

578
00:27:18,300 --> 00:27:22,390
That means that you should have
won maybe 60% of those bets?

579
00:27:22,410 --> 00:27:24,390
That's what I'm saying.
I'm due.

580
00:27:24,410 --> 00:27:27,290
You're cursed.
I'm cursed?

581
00:27:27,310 --> 00:27:29,500
I want to try something -
An experiment.

582
00:27:29,800 --> 00:27:32,000
I think I've got a deck
around here somewhere.

583
00:27:33,500 --> 00:27:34,300
Yeah.

584
00:27:35,200 --> 00:27:36,800
High card wins.

585
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:43,100
You want me to do that?

586
00:27:44,100 --> 00:27:45,900
I- I got it. I got it.

587
00:27:49,200 --> 00:27:50,100
All right.

588
00:27:57,000 --> 00:27:58,000
Again?

589
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:08,100
Damn.

590
00:28:08,800 --> 00:28:10,900
You want to
make it interesting?

591
00:28:11,500 --> 00:28:12,700
Sure.

592
00:28:13,300 --> 00:28:15,800
Okay, you're down 2-0.

593
00:28:16,300 --> 00:28:20,000
8 more cuts, 100 bucks a pop.
My money against your time.

594
00:28:20,300 --> 00:28:23,300
You win even one,
you get paid.

595
00:28:23,500 --> 00:28:26,090
I win all eight, you owe me
eight weeks at gamblers united.

596
00:28:26,110 --> 00:28:27,400
I'll sponsor you.

597
00:28:27,900 --> 00:28:29,600
0 for 10?

598
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:32,500
You're on.

599
00:29:12,400 --> 00:29:13,800
Damn!

600
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:18,600
What are the odds?

601
00:29:18,700 --> 00:29:20,900
Astronomical.

602
00:29:21,500 --> 00:29:23,500
<i>I am cursed.</i>

603
00:29:25,600 --> 00:29:28,590
You see, there's - There's
something I don't understand.

604
00:29:28,610 --> 00:29:32,290
How I can throw away my family,
my career, everything?

605
00:29:32,310 --> 00:29:35,190
<i>No, it's a disease, Leonard.
That I do understand.</i>

606
00:29:35,210 --> 00:29:36,190
Then what?

607
00:29:36,210 --> 00:29:38,300
Well, you say you crave
the action, but what action?

608
00:29:38,500 --> 00:29:42,000
What kind of thrill
can there be when you -

609
00:29:42,900 --> 00:29:47,000
When you know you're gonna
lose almost every time?

610
00:29:47,400 --> 00:29:49,100
Where's the fun in that?

611
00:29:53,700 --> 00:29:55,600
No more questions,
your honor.

612
00:29:56,700 --> 00:30:00,200
Ms. Crane, would you like
to cross-Examine this witness?

613
00:30:00,700 --> 00:30:02,090
I would, your honor.

614
00:30:02,110 --> 00:30:03,090
Proceed.

615
00:30:03,110 --> 00:30:05,590
Dr. Gallagher,
the defendant, Mr. Hansen,

616
00:30:05,610 --> 00:30:07,090
Isn't psychotic, is he?
No.

617
00:30:07,110 --> 00:30:09,390
Bipolar, schizophrenic, or delusional?
Nope.

618
00:30:09,410 --> 00:30:11,090
Clinically depressed
or suicidal?

619
00:30:11,110 --> 00:30:13,690
Addicted to any substance or
a pattern of aberrant behavior?

620
00:30:13,710 --> 00:30:14,390
No.

621
00:30:14,410 --> 00:30:16,390
Suffering from
any neurological disorder

622
00:30:16,410 --> 00:30:18,990
that might make him a danger
to himself or others?

623
00:30:19,010 --> 00:30:19,990
None.

624
00:30:20,010 --> 00:30:21,290
Would you describe
the conditions

625
00:30:21,310 --> 00:30:23,090
Magical thinking
and misattribution

626
00:30:23,110 --> 00:30:24,690
as serious mental diseases?

627
00:30:24,710 --> 00:30:27,800
No, but they can have serious
consequences, as in this case.

628
00:30:28,100 --> 00:30:29,490
Thank you for that
clarification, doctor.

629
00:30:29,510 --> 00:30:33,390
If I saw a burning bush
on my way home from work today

630
00:30:33,410 --> 00:30:36,590
And in the crackling sound
I heard the voice of god,

631
00:30:36,610 --> 00:30:39,800
Could I be described as having
lapsed into magical thinking?

632
00:30:40,300 --> 00:30:41,790
Well, that would
very much depend

633
00:30:41,810 --> 00:30:43,590
On what type of smoke
you'd inhaled

634
00:30:43,610 --> 00:30:45,290
And whether or not
you had much of a yearning

635
00:30:45,310 --> 00:30:47,500
To be a biblical prophet.

636
00:30:57,800 --> 00:30:59,690
Magical thinking, then,

637
00:30:59,710 --> 00:31:02,190
Represents
a kind of wish fulfillment,

638
00:31:02,210 --> 00:31:05,500
Seeing what one wants or needs
to see or experience?

639
00:31:05,800 --> 00:31:06,990
To a degree.

640
00:31:07,010 --> 00:31:10,090
Magical thinking
is wishful thinking.

641
00:31:10,110 --> 00:31:11,590
That's
an oversimplification.

642
00:31:11,610 --> 00:31:14,900
Is wishful thinking the product
of a diseased mind, doctor?

643
00:31:15,100 --> 00:31:16,490
No, but, um -

644
00:31:16,510 --> 00:31:17,790
Then I assume
it's entirely sane

645
00:31:17,810 --> 00:31:19,790
For us to act
to fulfill our wishes?

646
00:31:19,810 --> 00:31:20,690
Of course.

647
00:31:20,710 --> 00:31:25,490
Such as robbing and butchering a
man we perceive to be a threat?

648
00:31:25,510 --> 00:31:27,490
Objection.
Sustained.

649
00:31:27,510 --> 00:31:30,690
Misattribution - The conviction
that a false memory is true.

650
00:31:30,710 --> 00:31:31,590
More or less.

651
00:31:31,610 --> 00:31:32,790
A man witnesses a murder.

652
00:31:32,810 --> 00:31:35,090
He then remembers himself
not as a witness,

653
00:31:35,110 --> 00:31:36,890
But as having committed
the murder.

654
00:31:36,910 --> 00:31:38,790
I believe that's
exactly what happened.

655
00:31:38,810 --> 00:31:40,500
Well,
the defendant confessed...

656
00:31:41,300 --> 00:31:42,590
Then he un-Confessed.

657
00:31:42,610 --> 00:31:44,690
When his true memories
reasserted themselves.

658
00:31:44,710 --> 00:31:47,490
Or else, faced with the
possibility of incarceration

659
00:31:47,510 --> 00:31:50,400
Or execution
for premeditated murder,

660
00:31:50,600 --> 00:31:53,890
Mr. Hansen did a little more
magical thinking,

661
00:31:53,910 --> 00:31:56,290
Instead becoming
the blameless witness,

662
00:31:56,310 --> 00:31:58,700
Making the lie the memory.

663
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:03,800
Mr. Hansen has a history
of good behavior,

664
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:05,090
A steady job,

665
00:32:05,110 --> 00:32:07,790
Good relationships
with co-Workers, friends, and family

666
00:32:07,810 --> 00:32:10,990
Who universally describe him
as passive, shy,

667
00:32:11,010 --> 00:32:12,390
And very good-natured -

668
00:32:12,410 --> 00:32:14,590
No trouble with the police,
no acts of violence,

669
00:32:14,610 --> 00:32:16,490
Despite a lifetime
of being made fun of

670
00:32:16,510 --> 00:32:18,190
For being just
a little bit slow.

671
00:32:18,210 --> 00:32:19,690
That's Trey Hansen,

672
00:32:19,710 --> 00:32:22,290
Not the murderer
you're making him out to be

673
00:32:22,310 --> 00:32:24,600
For the sake
of winning this case.

674
00:32:32,300 --> 00:32:35,590
We know what, uh,
what you believe, doctor.

675
00:32:35,610 --> 00:32:36,790
You - You care
about your patient,

676
00:32:36,810 --> 00:32:38,790
And it also suits your case
to see him in that light.

677
00:32:38,810 --> 00:32:41,090
But what about Hansen himself?

678
00:32:41,110 --> 00:32:42,790
I'm curious -
How suggestible is he?

679
00:32:42,810 --> 00:32:45,500
Could you, for example,
reconvince him

680
00:32:46,200 --> 00:32:49,600
So that he, in fact, believes
he did murder Andrew Wohl?

681
00:32:50,300 --> 00:32:52,590
It's possible to implant
false memories.

682
00:32:52,610 --> 00:32:54,490
Could I,
hypothetically?

683
00:32:54,510 --> 00:32:55,900
Hypothetically.

684
00:32:56,200 --> 00:32:58,500
Given his ongoing condition,

685
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:00,990
Mr. Hansen
may never be 100% certain

686
00:33:01,010 --> 00:33:03,600
If he actually
is a murderer or not.

687
00:33:05,800 --> 00:33:06,900
Possibly not.

688
00:33:07,300 --> 00:33:09,800
Then how on earth
can you be so certain?

689
00:33:10,600 --> 00:33:12,900
<i>How on earth can you?</i>

690
00:33:13,500 --> 00:33:16,590
I have a defendant with a desire
and opportunity to kill.

691
00:33:16,610 --> 00:33:18,290
I have the murder weapon
in his possession.

692
00:33:18,310 --> 00:33:20,490
I have his clothing drenched
with the victim's blood.

693
00:33:20,510 --> 00:33:22,790
I have two confessions,
one unsolicited.

694
00:33:22,810 --> 00:33:25,200
I have evidence, doctor.

695
00:33:25,700 --> 00:33:27,500
Not wishful thinking.

696
00:33:28,100 --> 00:33:30,000
<i>I am certain.</i>

697
00:33:55,600 --> 00:33:57,100
That's how it's done.

698
00:33:58,700 --> 00:33:59,090
Winning?

699
00:33:59,110 --> 00:34:00,200
The job.

700
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:06,300
I gave you honest answers
without agenda.

701
00:34:06,500 --> 00:34:08,600
You took what I said -
You twisted it.

702
00:34:09,200 --> 00:34:10,590
You repackaged it

703
00:34:10,610 --> 00:34:12,800
And sold it to the jury
as something else.

704
00:34:13,100 --> 00:34:14,800
It's called advocacy.

705
00:34:15,100 --> 00:34:17,390
Lynn, as an advocate
for Mr. Hansen,

706
00:34:17,410 --> 00:34:20,590
Did a decent job
on your redirect.

707
00:34:20,610 --> 00:34:21,690
It tends to balance out.

708
00:34:21,710 --> 00:34:24,890
Sure, Lynn did a decent job,
but she's not in your league.

709
00:34:24,910 --> 00:34:26,190
You were better.
You were tougher.

710
00:34:26,210 --> 00:34:27,390
You were more driven.

711
00:34:27,410 --> 00:34:29,800
So a man ends up
guilty as charged.

712
00:34:30,200 --> 00:34:33,190
There's judge and jury.
There's court of appeals.

713
00:34:33,210 --> 00:34:35,800
I'm a small part
of the process.

714
00:34:37,100 --> 00:34:38,600
That's your excuse.

715
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:40,200
Why do I need one?

716
00:34:41,100 --> 00:34:43,100
Someday, Marcie, you may.

717
00:34:43,900 --> 00:34:47,000
I just hope when the time comes,
you'll know, uh...

718
00:34:47,800 --> 00:34:49,700
You'll know where
to find the help.

719
00:34:52,500 --> 00:34:54,100
Psychiatrist.

720
00:34:54,600 --> 00:34:56,600
It's all so clear to you.

721
00:34:57,700 --> 00:34:59,300
Do you think you know me?

722
00:34:59,500 --> 00:35:01,390
What if the jury
comes back not guilty?

723
00:35:01,410 --> 00:35:02,390
They won't.

724
00:35:02,410 --> 00:35:03,700
What if they do?

725
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:06,900
Will you think
you might have been wrong?

726
00:35:07,300 --> 00:35:09,890
Will you actually
take a look at Trey Hansen,

727
00:35:09,910 --> 00:35:12,590
Not as a prosecutor
but as a human being?

728
00:35:12,610 --> 00:35:13,590
Because if you did,

729
00:35:13,610 --> 00:35:17,790
You'd realize all the
so-Called facts in this case

730
00:35:17,810 --> 00:35:19,190
Prove nothing.

731
00:35:19,210 --> 00:35:22,300
The real win here
is to set him free.

732
00:35:23,800 --> 00:35:25,800
Set yourself free.

733
00:35:38,300 --> 00:35:40,000
Jury's back.

734
00:36:03,100 --> 00:36:06,490
"In the matter of the state
of california vs. Trey Hansen,

735
00:36:06,510 --> 00:36:08,700
"On the count
of premeditated murder,

736
00:36:08,800 --> 00:36:11,900
We, the jury,
find the defendant... "

737
00:36:36,100 --> 00:36:37,900
And you...

738
00:36:42,500 --> 00:36:47,400
"we, the jury,
find the defendant... "

739
00:37:00,500 --> 00:37:03,890
"We, the jury, find
the defendant, Trey Hansen... "

740
00:37:03,910 --> 00:37:05,000
Guilty.

741
00:37:05,200 --> 00:37:09,300
"... Guilty of murder
in the first degree. "

742
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:19,200
guilty.

743
00:37:24,100 --> 00:37:25,700
What really happened?

744
00:37:26,900 --> 00:37:29,200
Hansen was waiting for the bus,
just like he said -

745
00:37:29,900 --> 00:37:35,300
Wrong time, wrong place,
wrong emotional state.

746
00:37:40,700 --> 00:37:42,390
He saw the murder.
He saw everything.

747
00:37:42,410 --> 00:37:43,590
Resulting
in emotional shock,

748
00:37:43,610 --> 00:37:46,090
Magical thinking,
and misattribution.

749
00:37:46,110 --> 00:37:49,300
Here was his tormentor,
his enemy,

750
00:37:49,600 --> 00:37:51,490
Lying helpless at his feet.

751
00:37:51,510 --> 00:37:54,090
Who knows what Trey had imagined
on his own?

752
00:37:54,110 --> 00:37:57,600
Whatever it was,
this was so much more.

753
00:38:00,800 --> 00:38:02,190
What happened in the bar?

754
00:38:02,210 --> 00:38:03,490
They found the real killer
eventually.

755
00:38:03,510 --> 00:38:05,190
He had the victim's wallet,
and after he confessed,

756
00:38:05,210 --> 00:38:06,990
The police went back
to the rock garden

757
00:38:07,010 --> 00:38:08,800
And re-Interviewed
the witnesses.

758
00:38:13,100 --> 00:38:14,090
Wohl and his two buddies -

759
00:38:14,110 --> 00:38:16,200
They were regulars.
They knew the bartender.

760
00:38:16,400 --> 00:38:19,090
They had too much to drink that
night and started riding Hansen,

761
00:38:19,110 --> 00:38:21,490
You know, tripping him,
spilling beer on him.

762
00:38:21,510 --> 00:38:22,590
He didn't know
how to fight back.

763
00:38:22,610 --> 00:38:24,090
So he complained
to the bartender.

764
00:38:24,110 --> 00:38:27,200
<i>But when he did, he was the one
that got thrown out.</i>

765
00:38:27,700 --> 00:38:30,490
And everyone was very
contrite after Hansen died.

766
00:38:30,510 --> 00:38:32,190
That's when the truth
came out.

767
00:38:32,210 --> 00:38:33,290
Too late for Hansen.

768
00:38:33,310 --> 00:38:36,790
Strangled in his
holding cell,

769
00:38:36,810 --> 00:38:39,590
Waiting for transport to state
prison after the guilty verdict.

770
00:38:39,610 --> 00:38:44,000
And too late for Marcie Crane.
She had a complete breakdown.

771
00:38:45,400 --> 00:38:46,990
<i>I read about the case
in the journal,</i>

772
00:38:47,010 --> 00:38:48,800
Got in touch
with her doctors.

773
00:38:49,200 --> 00:38:50,990
That's when
we hatched the plan -

774
00:38:51,010 --> 00:38:52,590
You know,
to re-Enact the trial.

775
00:38:52,610 --> 00:38:53,890
How many times
have you tried?

776
00:38:53,910 --> 00:38:55,400
This was strike two.

777
00:38:55,600 --> 00:38:59,190
You see, all during
the trial, it rained.

778
00:38:59,210 --> 00:39:00,490
So, whenever it rains

779
00:39:00,510 --> 00:39:01,990
For more than a couple
of days in a row -

780
00:39:02,010 --> 00:39:03,590
She relives it.

781
00:39:03,610 --> 00:39:05,000
Yeah.

782
00:39:05,200 --> 00:39:07,290
For Marcie,
winning is a reflex.

783
00:39:07,310 --> 00:39:09,300
She won't give in.
She doesn't know how.

784
00:39:09,500 --> 00:39:10,290
So, it's no good,

785
00:39:10,310 --> 00:39:12,890
Us just pronouncing
Trey Hansen innocent.

786
00:39:12,910 --> 00:39:14,790
We tried it the first time.
It doesn't work.

787
00:39:14,810 --> 00:39:17,990
We have to somehow build a case
that's convincing enough

788
00:39:18,010 --> 00:39:20,100
So that Marcie
is willing to lose.

789
00:39:21,100 --> 00:39:23,200
At least,
that's the theory, anyway.

790
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:26,100
Next time,
can I play Hansen?

791
00:39:26,900 --> 00:39:28,700
I don't know.
Can you?

792
00:39:37,400 --> 00:39:38,490
I'll meet you downstairs.

793
00:39:38,510 --> 00:39:39,600
Okay.

794
00:39:40,800 --> 00:39:42,290
We came closer this time.

795
00:39:42,310 --> 00:39:44,890
She almost tripped up over
the new memorandum to the court

796
00:39:44,910 --> 00:39:46,500
And the new diagnosis.

797
00:39:46,700 --> 00:39:48,700
Then there was
the plea-Bargain offer.

798
00:39:49,000 --> 00:39:51,590
Also, she opened up to you
more than she has.

799
00:39:51,610 --> 00:39:53,900
She even hesitated before
pronouncing the verdict.

800
00:39:54,400 --> 00:39:55,990
You nearly
got to her, Jack.

801
00:39:56,010 --> 00:39:59,490
Yeah, but in the end,
her verdict was the same.

802
00:39:59,510 --> 00:40:02,590
Don't be discouraged, doctor.
We'll try again.

803
00:40:02,610 --> 00:40:04,200
Next rainy days.

804
00:40:04,400 --> 00:40:06,190
I'm sorry, denny,
but what am I supposed to do?

805
00:40:06,210 --> 00:40:07,790
Half the staff's
still out with the same bug,

806
00:40:07,810 --> 00:40:10,000
And they need me
to cover for a while.

807
00:40:10,900 --> 00:40:11,690
Uh...

808
00:40:11,710 --> 00:40:13,390
Well, that - That's sweet,
but don't bother.

809
00:40:13,410 --> 00:40:16,190
I'll, uh, I'll get
something to eat

810
00:40:16,210 --> 00:40:19,000
When I, uh,
when I-I get home.

811
00:40:20,100 --> 00:40:22,800
Yeah, no, I mean, uh,
before I leave.

812
00:40:24,600 --> 00:40:25,890
Okay.

813
00:40:25,910 --> 00:40:28,800
Yeah, I-I love you, too.
Bye.

814
00:40:31,700 --> 00:40:33,000
All clear?

815
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:36,100
I have to be home
by 11:00.

816
00:40:36,900 --> 00:40:38,200
That'll have to do.

817
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:51,600
Oh, hey, wait up!

818
00:40:52,500 --> 00:40:53,600
Hey!

819
00:40:54,200 --> 00:40:55,590
Mort's?
Where else?

820
00:40:55,610 --> 00:40:56,900
Pastrami?

821
00:40:57,100 --> 00:41:00,000
Uh, brisket...
with new pickles.

822
00:41:00,500 --> 00:41:01,800
sounds good.

823
00:41:04,200 --> 00:41:07,300
Y- You know, you don't
have to go in with me.

824
00:41:08,600 --> 00:41:10,000
Confession time?

825
00:41:10,400 --> 00:41:13,000
When we cut the cards,
I stacked the deck.

826
00:41:13,700 --> 00:41:15,400
I, uh, figured.

827
00:41:15,700 --> 00:41:17,700
We're not so different,
you and I.

828
00:41:19,700 --> 00:41:21,500
I'm scared, doc.

829
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:25,790
I mean, uh, eight meetings
of gamblers united -

830
00:41:25,810 --> 00:41:26,590
That was the deal.

831
00:41:26,610 --> 00:41:29,600
So why am I scared?

832
00:41:31,900 --> 00:41:35,100
Well, maybe
because this time...

833
00:41:35,800 --> 00:41:38,200
There's actually something
important at stake.

834
00:41:40,000 --> 00:41:42,300
Win some, lose some, right?

835
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:45,200
Right.

